Note:
Runa Standard Library: Set Utilities

Provides comprehensive set operations for creating, manipulating, and querying unordered collections of unique elements. 
Idiomatic Runa code uses set literals, comprehensions, and helper processes for advanced or programmatic use cases.

Advanced features include:
- Core set operations (add, remove, contains, clear)
- Bulk operations and batch processing
- Set theory operations (union, intersection, difference)
- Searching and filtering operations
- Set transformations and mapping
- Performance optimizations
- Thread-safe operations (when supported)
:End Note

Note: Core Set Operations
Process called "from_list" that takes elements as List[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Let s be set containing
    For each e in elements:
        Add e to s
    Return s

Process called "create_empty_set" that returns Set[Any]:
    Return set containing

Process called "add" that takes s as Set[Any] and value as Any returns Set[Any]:
    Return s plus set containing value

Process called "add_multiple" that takes s as Set[Any] and values as List[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Let result be s
    For each value in values:
        Set result to result plus set containing value
    Return result

Process called "remove" that takes s as Set[Any] and value as Any returns Set[Any]:
    Return s minus set containing value

Process called "remove_safe" that takes s as Set[Any] and value as Any returns Set[Any]:
    If value is in s:
        Return s minus set containing value
    Return s

Process called "discard" that takes s as Set[Any] and value as Any returns Set[Any]:
    Return remove_safe with s as s and value as value

Process called "pop" that takes s as Set[Any] returns (Set[Any], Any):
    If length of s is equal to 0:
        Throw KeyError with message "Cannot pop from empty set"
    Let elements be list containing
    For each element in s:
        Add element to elements
    Let value be elements[0]
    Return (s minus set containing value, value)

Process called "clear" that takes s as Set[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Return set containing

Process called "copy" that takes s as Set[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Let result be set containing
    For each element in s:
        Add element to result
    Return result

Process called "deep_copy" that takes s as Set[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Let result be set containing
    For each element in s:
        If element is set:
            Add deep_copy with s as element to result
        Otherwise if element is list:
            Add deep_copy_list_helper with lst as element to result
        Otherwise if element is dictionary:
            Add deep_copy_dict_helper with d as element to result
        Otherwise:
            Add element to result
    Return result

Note: Query and Analysis Operations
Process called "contains" that takes s as Set[Any] and value as Any returns Boolean:
    Return value is in s

Process called "size" that takes s as Set[Any] returns Integer:
    Return length of s

Process called "is_empty" that takes s as Set[Any] returns Boolean:
    Return length of s is equal to 0

Process called "elements" that takes s as Set[Any] returns List[Any]:
    Let result be list containing
    For each element in s:
        Add element to result
    Return result

Process called "has_element" that takes s as Set[Any] and value as Any returns Boolean:
    Return value is in s

Process called "is_subset" that takes s1 as Set[Any] and s2 as Set[Any] returns Boolean:
    For each element in s1:
        If not element is in s2:
            Return false
    Return true

Process called "is_superset" that takes s1 as Set[Any] and s2 as Set[Any] returns Boolean:
    Return is_subset with s1 as s2 and s2 as s1

Process called "is_proper_subset" that takes s1 as Set[Any] and s2 as Set[Any] returns Boolean:
    Return is_subset with s1 as s1 and s2 as s2 and length of s1 is less than length of s2

Process called "is_proper_superset" that takes s1 as Set[Any] and s2 as Set[Any] returns Boolean:
    Return is_proper_subset with s1 as s2 and s2 as s1

Process called "is_disjoint" that takes s1 as Set[Any] and s2 as Set[Any] returns Boolean:
    For each element in s1:
        If element is in s2:
            Return false
    Return true

Note: Set Theory Operations
Process called "union" that takes s1 as Set[Any] and s2 as Set[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Return s1 plus s2

Process called "union_multiple" that takes sets as List[Set[Any]] returns Set[Any]:
    If length of sets is equal to 0:
        Return set containing
    Let result be sets[0]
    For i from 1 to length of sets:
        Set result to result plus sets[i]
    Return result

Process called "intersection" that takes s1 as Set[Any] and s2 as Set[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Let result be set containing
    For each element in s1:
        If element is in s2:
            Add element to result
    Return result

Process called "intersection_multiple" that takes sets as List[Set[Any]] returns Set[Any]:
    If length of sets is equal to 0:
        Return set containing
    Let result be sets[0]
    For i from 1 to length of sets:
        Set result to intersection with s1 as result and s2 as sets[i]
    Return result

Process called "difference" that takes s1 as Set[Any] and s2 as Set[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Return s1 minus s2

Process called "difference_multiple" that takes sets as List[Set[Any]] returns Set[Any]:
    If length of sets is equal to 0:
        Return set containing
    Let result be sets[0]
    For i from 1 to length of sets:
        Set result to result minus sets[i]
    Return result

Process called "symmetric_difference" that takes s1 as Set[Any] and s2 as Set[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Let union_set be s1 plus s2
    Let intersection_set be intersection with s1 as s1 and s2 as s2
    Return union_set minus intersection_set

Process called "complement" that takes s as Set[Any] and universe as Set[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Return universe minus s

Note: Bulk Operations
Process called "update" that takes s as Set[Any] and other as Set[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Return s plus other

Process called "update_multiple" that takes s as Set[Any] and others as List[Set[Any]] returns Set[Any]:
    Let result be s
    For each other in others:
        Set result to result plus other
    Return result

Process called "intersection_update" that takes s as Set[Any] and other as Set[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Return intersection with s1 as s and s2 as other

Process called "intersection_update_multiple" that takes s as Set[Any] and others as List[Set[Any]] returns Set[Any]:
    Let result be s
    For each other in others:
        Set result to intersection with s1 as result and s2 as other
    Return result

Process called "difference_update" that takes s as Set[Any] and other as Set[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Return s minus other

Process called "difference_update_multiple" that takes s as Set[Any] and others as List[Set[Any]] returns Set[Any]:
    Let result be s
    For each other in others:
        Set result to result minus other
    Return result

Process called "symmetric_difference_update" that takes s as Set[Any] and other as Set[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Return symmetric_difference with s1 as s and s2 as other

Note: Filtering and Transformation Operations
Process called "filter" that takes s as Set[Any] and predicate as Process returns Set[Any]:
    Let result be set containing
    For each element in s:
        If predicate with element as element:
            Add element to result
    Return result

Process called "filter_not" that takes s as Set[Any] and predicate as Process returns Set[Any]:
    Let result be set containing
    For each element in s:
        If not predicate with element as element:
            Add element to result
    Return result

Process called "map" that takes s as Set[Any] and transform as Process returns Set[Any]:
    Let result be set containing
    For each element in s:
        Add transform with element as element to result
    Return result

Process called "flat_map" that takes s as Set[Any] and transform as Process returns Set[Any]:
    Let result be set containing
    For each element in s:
        Let transformed be transform with element as element
        For each sub_element in transformed:
            Add sub_element to result
    Return result

Process called "partition" that takes s as Set[Any] and predicate as Process returns (Set[Any], Set[Any]):
    Let true_set be set containing
    Let false_set be set containing
    For each element in s:
        If predicate with element as element:
            Add element to true_set
        Otherwise:
            Add element to false_set
    Return (true_set, false_set)

Note: Utility Operations
Process called "from_keys" that takes keys as List[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Let result be set containing
    For each key in keys:
        Add key to result
    Return result

Process called "from_values" that takes values as List[Any] returns Set[Any]:
    Return from_keys with keys as values

Process called "group_by" that takes items as List[Any] and key_func as Process returns Dictionary[Any, Set[Any]]:
    Let result be dictionary with:
    For each item in items:
        Let key be key_func with item as item
        If key in result:
            Add item to result[key]
        Otherwise:
            Set result[key] to set containing item
    Return result

Process called "count_by" that takes items as List[Any] and key_func as Process returns Dictionary[Any, Integer]:
    Let result be dictionary with:
    For each item in items:
        Let key be key_func with item as item
        If key in result:
            Set result[key] to result[key] plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Set result[key] to 1
    Return result

Process called "any" that takes s as Set[Any] and predicate as Process returns Boolean:
    For each element in s:
        If predicate with element as element:
            Return true
    Return false

Process called "all" that takes s as Set[Any] and predicate as Process returns Boolean:
    For each element in s:
        If not predicate with element as element:
            Return false
    Return true

Process called "none" that takes s as Set[Any] and predicate as Process returns Boolean:
    Return not any with s as s and predicate as predicate

Process called "find" that takes s as Set[Any] and predicate as Process returns Dictionary:
    For each element in s:
        If predicate with element as element:
            Return dictionary with:
                found as true
                value as element
    Return dictionary with:
        found as false
        value as None

Process called "find_all" that takes s as Set[Any] and predicate as Process returns Set[Any]:
    Let result be set containing
    For each element in s:
        If predicate with element as element:
            Add element to result
    Return result

Process called "min_element" that takes s as Set[Number] returns Dictionary:
    If length of s is equal to 0:
        Return dictionary with:
            found as false
            value as 0
    Let elements_list be elements with s as s
    Let min_val be elements_list[0]
    For each element in elements_list:
        If element is less than min_val:
            Set min_val to element
    Return dictionary with:
        found as true
        value as min_val

Process called "max_element" that takes s as Set[Number] returns Dictionary:
    If length of s is equal to 0:
        Return dictionary with:
            found as false
            value as 0
    Let elements_list be elements with s as s
    Let max_val be elements_list[0]
    For each element in elements_list:
        If element is greater than max_val:
            Set max_val to element
    Return dictionary with:
        found as true
        value as max_val

Process called "sum_elements" that takes s as Set[Number] returns Number:
    Let total be 0
    For each element in s:
        Set total to total plus element
    Return total

Process called "average_elements" that takes s as Set[Number] returns Number:
    Let size be length of s
    If size is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    Return sum_elements with s as s divided by size

Process called "product_elements" that takes s as Set[Number] returns Number:
    Let total be 1
    For each element in s:
        Set total to total multiplied by element
    Return total

Process called "powerset" that takes s as Set[Any] returns Set[Set[Any]]:
    Let elements be elements of s
    Let n be length of elements
    Let result be set containing
    For i from 0 to power_helper with base as 2 and exponent as n:
        Let subset be set containing
        For j from 0 to n:
            If remainder of i divided by power_helper with base as 2 and exponent as j plus 1 is greater than or equal to power_helper with base as 2 and exponent as j:
                Add elements[j] to subset
        Add subset to result
    Return result

Process called "cartesian_product" that takes s1 as Set[Any] and s2 as Set[Any] returns Set[Tuple[Any, Any]]:
    Let result be set containing
    For each element1 in s1:
        For each element2 in s2:
            Add (element1, element2) to result
    Return result

Process called "cartesian_product_multiple" that takes sets as List[Set[Any]] returns Set[List[Any]]:
    If length of sets is equal to 0:
        Return set containing list containing
    If length of sets is equal to 1:
        Let result be set containing
        For each element in sets[0]:
            Add [element] to result
        Return result
    Let first_set be sets[0]
    Let rest_sets be slice_list_helper with lst as sets and start as 1 and end as length of sets
    Let rest_product be cartesian_product_multiple with sets as rest_sets
    Let result be set containing
    For each element in first_set:
        For each combination in rest_product:
            Add concatenate_lists_helper with lst1 as list containing element and lst2 as combination to result
    Return result

Note: Helper Functions for Set Operations
Process called "deep_copy_list_helper" that takes lst as List[Any] returns List[Any]:
    Let result be list containing
    For each element in lst:
        If element is set:
            Add deep_copy with s as element to result
        Otherwise if element is list:
            Add deep_copy_list_helper with lst as element to result
        Otherwise if element is dictionary:
            Add deep_copy_dict_helper with d as element to result
        Otherwise:
            Add element to result
    Return result

Process called "deep_copy_dict_helper" that takes d as Dictionary[Any, Any] returns Dictionary[Any, Any]:
    Let result be dictionary with:
    For each key and value in d:
        If value is set:
            Set result[key] to deep_copy with s as value
        Otherwise if value is list:
            Set result[key] to deep_copy_list_helper with lst as value
        Otherwise if value is dictionary:
            Set result[key] to deep_copy_dict_helper with d as value
        Otherwise:
            Set result[key] to value
    Return result

Process called "slice_list_helper" that takes lst as List[Any] and start as Integer and end as Integer returns List[Any]:
    Let result be list containing
    If start is less than 0:
        Set start to 0
    If end is greater than length of lst:
        Set end to length of lst
    For i from start to end minus 1:
        Add lst[i] to result
    Return result

Process called "concatenate_lists_helper" that takes lst1 as List[Any] and lst2 as List[Any] returns List[Any]:
    Let result be list containing
    For each element in lst1:
        Add element to result
    For each element in lst2:
        Add element to result
    Return result

Process called "power_helper" that takes base as Integer and exponent as Integer returns Integer:
    If exponent is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    If exponent is equal to 1:
        Return base
    
    Let result be 1
    For i from 1 to exponent:
        Set result to result multiplied by base
    Return result

Process called "copy_helper" that takes lst as List[Any] returns List[Any]:
    Let result be list containing
    For each element in lst:
        Add element to result
    Return result